{{notability|date=November 2014}}
The '''relational meeting''' is a primary organizing tool used by the [[Industrial Areas Foundation]]<ref>[[Edward T. Chambers]] with Michael A Cowan, ''Roots for Radicals: Organizing for Power, Action , and Justice'' (New York: Continuum, 2004), Ch. 2, pp. 44-54.</ref> and other [[Congregation-based Community Organizing| congregation-based community organizing]] groups including [[Gamaliel Foundation]] and [[PICO National Network]] &ndash; and also often in union organizing.  It consists of a one-on-one, face-to-face meeting of two persons lasting at least 30 minutes, where personal topics and stories dealing with values, motivations, self-interest and life are discussed in an often confessional, cathartic sort of manner.<ref>Dennis A. Jacobsen, ''Doing Justice: Congregations and Community Organizing'' (Minneapolis: Fortress Press, 2001), Ch. 7, pp. 59-64.</ref>

